1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,400
Next type of exception we'll look at is the look up error.

2

00:00:03,400  -->  00:00:06,640
Imagine you're at the theme parks Lost and Found.

3

00:00:06,640  -->  00:00:10,620
Someone comes up looking for a lost item, but it's not in the system.

4

00:00:10,620  -->  00:00:15,000
This doesn't always mean that it's the system or your park's fault.

5

00:00:15,000  -->  00:00:18,900
Perhaps someone believes they left their bag at your park,

6

00:00:18,900  -->  00:00:21,700
but in reality, they never brought it to the park,

7

00:00:21,700  -->  00:00:24,540
and it's in fact still in their car in the parking lot.

8

00:00:24,540  -->  00:00:27,520
But if they request a search through your Lost and found,

9

00:00:27,520  -->  00:00:30,460
it would make sense that the item would not be found.

10

00:00:30,460  -->  00:00:32,300
Not only is it not in the system,

11

00:00:32,300  -->  00:00:34,940
but it was never in the park to begin with.

12

00:00:34,940  -->  00:00:38,120
Look up error acts as a general error

13

00:00:38,120  -->  00:00:41,160
that Python raises when it can't find what it's looking for,

14

00:00:41,160  -->  00:00:44,800
whether it's an item in a list or a key in a dictionary.

15

00:00:44,800  -->  00:00:50,760
This look up error based class covers specific errors like index error and key error,

16

00:00:50,760  -->  00:00:52,305
which we'll explore next.

17

00:00:52,305  -->  00:00:54,540
Let's talk about look up error.

18

00:00:54,540  -->  00:00:56,700
To see this in action,

19

00:00:56,700  -->  00:01:00,600
let's continue with our Lost and Found example from earlier.

20

00:01:00,600  -->  00:01:03,025
In our Lost and Found checker function,

21

00:01:03,025  -->  00:01:06,190
globally define our lost and found dictionary,

22

00:01:06,190  -->  00:01:08,490
where we have one pair of sunglasses,

23

00:01:08,490  -->  00:01:11,310
two hats, and three water bottles.

24

00:01:11,310  -->  00:01:15,510
If somebody were to come up to your Lost and Found asking for a bag,

25

00:01:15,510  -->  00:01:18,490
this item in question of bag would be

26

00:01:18,490  -->  00:01:22,010
an argument sent into our Check Lost and Found function.

27

00:01:22,010  -->  00:01:24,630
So let's write some code to illustrate this.

28

00:01:24,630  -->  00:01:26,470
We'll define our dictionary like this,

29

00:01:26,470  -->  00:01:28,610
where we'll say Lost and Found equals,

30

00:01:28,610  -->  00:01:31,110
and then in squiggly brackets,

31

00:01:31,110  -->  00:01:33,485
we'll say sunglasses with one,

32

00:01:33,485  -->  00:01:36,740
hat with two and water bottle with three,

33

00:01:36,740  -->  00:01:41,800
indicating how many items there are of each of these categories of items.

34

00:01:41,800  -->  00:01:45,200
Next, we'll define our check lost and found function,

35

00:01:45,200  -->  00:01:48,925
or we'll say deaf, check, lost,

36

00:01:48,925  -->  00:01:53,050
and found and then we'll say item in

37

00:01:53,050  -->  00:02:00,175
question as a parameter to pass into our function then try,

38

00:02:00,175  -->  00:02:04,530
and this will say print, lost and found.

39

00:02:04,530  -->  00:02:12,690
Then we will look for the key of item in question for the index.

40

00:02:12,690  -->  00:02:19,090
Then, otherwise, we're going to have a look up error as E,

41

00:02:19,090  -->  00:02:21,850
and then we'll say print F string,

42

00:02:21,850  -->  00:02:26,205
we'll say item, not found in lost and found.

43

00:02:26,205  -->  00:02:28,810
We'll have a E to return that error,

44

00:02:28,810  -->  00:02:30,370
we'll close out our string,

45

00:02:30,370  -->  00:02:34,790
close out our print statement and then what we'll do is we'll copy this function,

46

00:02:34,790  -->  00:02:37,090
and then as an argument,

47

00:02:37,090  -->  00:02:40,550
we'll pass in bag because this is the item that we want to

48

00:02:40,550  -->  00:02:43,950
check if this is in our check lost and found function,

49

00:02:43,950  -->  00:02:46,670
which then checks our lost and found object,

50

00:02:46,670  -->  00:02:48,310
which is our dictionary there.

51

00:02:48,310  -->  00:02:51,660
If we run this function, What do you think we'll see?

52

00:02:51,660  -->  00:02:53,320
When we run this function,

53

00:02:53,320  -->  00:02:58,160
we will see item not found in lost and found bag.

54

00:02:58,160  -->  00:03:01,020
This error is actually a key error,

55

00:03:01,020  -->  00:03:05,000
which we will learn about in a moment as a type of look up error.

56

00:03:05,000  -->  00:03:08,180
But most importantly, the look up error is fired off

57

00:03:08,180  -->  00:03:12,360
because the item bag is not found in the dictionary, Lost and Found.

58

00:03:12,360  -->  00:03:15,440
There's only sunglasses, hat, and water bottle.

59

00:03:15,440  -->  00:03:19,900
Using look up in this way provides us with flexibility for handling

60

00:03:19,900  -->  00:03:26,580
both key error and index error without needing separate except clauses for each.
